article.description: Tari Phillips hasn't forgotten last year's loss to Charlotte that kept New York out of the playoffs.
article.headline: Liberty win fourth straight
article.linkText: Liberty swat down Sting, maintain East lead
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Tari Phillips hasn't forgotten last
year's loss to Charlotte that kept New York out of the playoffs.

Motivated by those memories, Phillips scored 10 of her 12 points
in the final seven minutes and the Liberty held on to beat the
Sting 63-53 on Tuesday night.

Vickie Johnson added 15 points and Shameka Christon had 11 for
the Liberty (4-1), who won their fourth straight game and held onto
first place in the Eastern Conference.

Last year, the Sting knocked the Liberty out of the postseason
with an overtime win in the final game of the regular season. It
was only the second time in franchise history that New York missed
the playoffs.

"Tari is the type of player who never forgets those type of
things," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "She took over down
the stretch."

The Sting cut a 13-point second-half deficit to 43-39 on a
jumper by Tynesha Lewis with 7:47 to go.

Phillips responded with a driving basket, a turnaround jumper, a
layup and two free throws after an offensive rebound in an 8-3 run.
The Sting got no closer than six points after that.

"They put us out last year and there's a rivalry between us,"
Phillips said. "I looked up one time and said we have to put some
distance between us and secure this win. We played like this was a
playoff game."

Charlotte Smith-Taylor had a career-high 18 points for the Sting
(2-2), who were looking for their third straight win. Tammy
Sutton-Brown added 11 points and eight rebounds.

"We lost so I'm not really proud (of the career high) right
now," Smith-Taylor said. "We had a lot of defensive letdowns and
we gave them a lot of easy opportunities to score."

Two of Charlotte's top scorers, Allison Feaster and Andrea
Stinson, were held to a total of 10 points on 4-of-10 shooting.

Charlotte shot just 40 percent and committed 15 turnovers as it
fell to 1-2 at home. Last year, the Sting went 13-4 in Charlotte.

"They didn't do anything we didn't expect them to do, we just
did a poor job of defending them one-on-one," Sting coach Trudi
Lacey said. "Overall our focus was not where it needed to be."

Becky Hammon and Christon hit consecutive 3-pointers in an 8-0
run to give the Liberty a 20-10 lead with 9:52 left in the first
half. Christon's third 3-pointer made it 31-20 at halftime.

Phillips' runner in the lane to open the second half gave the
Liberty their largest lead.

New York hadn't won four in a row since July 2002.
